ce:section.ce:para:
Sunlight conversion film is a type of functional film which can alter the wavelength of light that displays prospective application in agriculture field. The blue (400–500 nm) and red light (600–680 nm) absorption encouraged the synthesis of chlorophyll for plant whereas below 400 nm UV light hindered the natural growth of plants and causing disease from insect pests [

                        1

                     ,

                        2

                     ]. Further, the sunlight conversion properties have important role in packaging prospect. Polymers are extensively used for food packaging application owing to their good processability, economical attractiveness, flexibility, mechanical strength and recyclability. Unfortunately, there are no such polymers which can completely block gas with allowing UV radiation through it. However, many products like dairy products need to be protected not only from gas as well as UV radiation also [

                        3

                     ]. Hence, it is noteworthy to develop sunlight conversion film to convert the light in ultraviolet region to blue light of wavelength 400–500 nm. Previously, different types of phosphors have been reported as sunlight conversion agent for instance Ba3MgSi2O8:Eu2+ 
                     [

                        4

                     ], and CaAl2O4:Eu2+ 
                     [

                        5

                     ]. In comparison to these phosphors, zero dimensional tiny C-dots an emerging new class of fluorescent nanomaterials, have inspired extensive consideration owing to their interesting attributes, such as high photostability, biocompatibility, low cytotoxicity and tunable excitation and emission [

                        6–10

                     ]. These outstanding performances endowed C-dots as promising candidate in sensing [

                        11–17

                     ], catalysis [

                        18

                     ], antibacterial property [

                        19

                     ], bioimaging [

                        20–23

                     ], energy conversion or storage devices [

                        24

                     ,

                        25

                     ], light emitting device [

                        26

                     ] and drug delivery [

                        27–30

                     ]. After the discovery of luminescence C-dots by Xu et al. [

                        31

                     ], a variety of approaches for synthesizing C-dots have been employed viz. arc discharge, acidic oxidation, oxygen plasma treatment, solvothermal, and laser ablation [

                        27

                     ,

                        32

                     ]. However, many researcher have taken efforts to prepare C-dots using inexpensive and environmental friendly precursors for instance yeast [

                        33

                     ], bamboo leaves [

                        34

                     ], grass [

                        35

                     ], and grape juice [

                        36

                     ] as the green sources for C-dots. These methods persuaded great interest due to their green chemistry nature in comparison to other fluorescence nanoparticles, like semiconductor quantum dots and noble metal nanoparticles.

The morphology and chemical structure of the GC-dots were studied by various characterization methods. TEM image revealed the as-prepared C-dots were well dispersed and spherical in morphology (Fig. 1a). As presented in Fig. 1b, the narrow size distribution histogram displayed a Gaussian fittings curve and showed that the average size of the GC-dots was approximately 2.0 nm, which was similar to the study reported previously [

                           39

                        ]. The selected area electron diffraction (SAED) image (inset of Fig. 1b) displayed diffused rings which indicated the amorphous phase of the carbon. The AFM topography image of GC-dots was analyzed on a silicon substrate. The as-prepared GC-dots were quasi-spherical and the topographic height showed in Fig.S2. The elemental compositions of the GC-dots were examined by Energy dispersive X-ray (EDX) spectroscopy and the distributions were monitored by mapping as shown in Fig.S3. The mass and the atomic ratio of the Carbon (C), Oxygen (O), Nitrogen (N), Sulphur (S) were 62.00: 32.76: 0.87: 0.81 and 70.40: 27.93: 0.42: 0.28, respectively.

To investigate the structure and composition of the as-prepared GC-dots FT-IR spectroscopy was measured (Fig. 2a). The peaks at around 2903 and 2828 cm−1 were related to the C − H stretching vibrations. The notable peak at 1590 cm−1 was assigned to the CC and CN stretching. The broad peak in the region 3280 cm−1 associated with the O − H and/or N − H bond stretching, which is propitious to improve the hydrophilicity of the C-dots. The peak located at 1365 cm−1 was ascribed to sp2 − CH in olefinic configuration [

                           40

                        ]. The peaks obtained at 2351, 1122, and 1761 cm−1 can be indexed to C − N, C − O − C, CO stretching vibrations, respectively. The peak at 755 cm−1 was ascribed to CH out-of-plane bending vibrations of benzene which suggests the presence of the aromatic rings on the GC-dots surface [

                           41

                        ,

                           42

                        ]. These oxygen-containing surface functional groups of the as-prepared C-dots would help them to be well dispersed in polar solvents, such as water, ethanol, dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO), and PBS, which are of huge benefit for biomedical applications. The surface composition of the GC-dots was studied by XPS measurements. The XPS survey spectrum (Fig. 2b) showed peaks associated with carbon (284.0 eV), nitrogen (400.3 eV), oxygen (53.0 eV), and sulphur (168.7 eV). The high resolution spectrum of C1s (Fig. 2c) revealed three peaks at 284.6, 285.6, and 287.7 eV which can be assigned to sp2 carbon (C=C), sp3 carbon (C − S, C − N, C − O (alkoxy and epoxy) and CO carbon, respectively [

                           43

                        ,

                           44

                        ]. The high resolution N1 s spectrum (Fig. 2d) can be deconvoluted into two different peaks which were associated with the presence of both pyridinic (399.9 eV) and pyrrolic type (401.25 eV) nitrogen in the C-dots [

                           45

                        ]. The presence of enormous hydrophilic groups at the surface of the GC-dots results in good water solubility. The S2p spectrum (Fig.S4a) comprised of three different peaks centered at about 163.8, 166.0, 167.9 eV. The former two peaks were ascribed to 2p3/2 and 2p1/2 of the –C-S covalent bond due to their spin-orbit coupling [

                           45

                        ]. The latter peak can be deconvoluted into three different peaks at 167.4, 168.0, 169.4 eV arising from –C–SOx– (x = 2, 3, 4) species [

                           45

                        ]. The 1H NMR experiment was performed to evaluate different chemical environments present in the GC-dots. The 1H NMR spectrum (Fig.S4b) was studied in D2O which unveiled signals in three different chemical regions. Peaks in the chemical environments 1 to 3 ppm and 3 to 6 ppm are assigned to the sp3 C − H protons and protons attached with carbonyl, hydroxyl and ether groups at the surface of the nano-dots. The region 6 to 8 ppm was responsible for the aromatic or sp2 protons [

                           41

                        ]. Moreover, to acquire the idea about the reproducibility, we prepared GC-dots in double (two batches) maintaining all the synthesis conditions same. The DLS measurement of GC-dots prepared for all the batches were recorded. For the two batches almost negligible particle sizes differences was obtained which indicated that the synthesis of GC-dots was reproducible (Fig.S5).

The UV–vis absorption spectrum represents two absorption peaks at 252 and 325 nm (Fig. 3a). The absorption peak at 252 nm and 325 nm were ascribed to the π-π* transition of the CC and CN bond of the aromatic sp2 domain and n-π* transition of the CO bond, respectively. The aqueous solution of GC-dots was light brown under daylight and displayed green fluorescence under illumination of UV light at 365 nm (inset of Fig. 3a). The detailed fluorescence emission spectra of GC-dots with different excitation wavelength were also examined. The emissions of the C-dots were found to be dependent on the wavelength of excitation. When the excitation wavelength increases from 320 to 460 nm the emission peak position red shifted from 446 to 545 nm. The excitation dependent and red-shifted optical property of the GC-dots was demonstrated in Fig. 3b. These behaviors caused from the different sizes of the C-dots and distribution of several surface states due to the different functional groups present on the surface [
46
]. The GC-dots showed maximum emission at 494 nm when excited at 400 nm (Fig.S6a). The photoluminescence property of the prepared GC-dots in different pH solutions was investigated. From Fig. 3c it can be seen that in the range of pH 4 to 11, the GC-dots (concentration of 0.01 g/mL) emits strong fluorescence when excited at 380 nm. The average fluorescence lifetime (Fig. 3d) of the GC-dots is 3.47 ns, such a small nanosecond magnitude of lifetime indicates that these nano-dots are appropriate for biological and optoelectronic application [
47
]. We measured the influence of ionic strength on the stability of the GC-dots in aqueous solution containing different concentrations (0.25–2.0 M) of NaCl. Slight decrease in FL response (Fig.S6b) was noticed even for a high concentration of NaCl solution (2.0 M). This result unveiled that C-dots have excellent stability at high ionic strength conditions. Furthermore, we performed the effect of different physiological conditions on the FL intensity of the C-dots. The FL intensity of GC-dots scarcely changed by different physiological conditions (Fig.S6c) such as 0.15 mM NaCl, pH 7.4, 10 mM tris-HCl. We also measured the effect of FL intensity over an extended time period. Fig.S6d showed that after 60 days of storage FL intensity of the GC-dots was not significantly changed (λex = 380 nm). Owing to the outstanding photoluminescent properties of C-dots, the GC-dots aqueous solution displayed much stronger resistance to photo-bleaching than the commercial organic dye fluorescein isothiocyanate (FITC). From Fig.S6e it can be seen that no significant reductions in fluorescence intensity were observed in GC-dots after continuous exposure to UV light for 60 min. The FL response of the GC-dots still reserved 94%, while decrement in FL intensity of FITC was observed to 29% of its original value. These showed that GC-dots were very stable and retain its fluorescence property for long time. The temporal stability of the C-dots was measured within 1 week time period in PBS and FBS buffer Fig.S7. The data showed that the C-dots were very stable in both PBS and FBS and showed almost negligible particle sizes differences within 1 week period. The zeta potential of the GC-dots was stable during 1 week observation in PBS buffer. The measured zeta potentials were − 2.1 mV (0 days), −2.0 mV (3 days), and − 2.0 mV (7 days). The fluorescence quantum yield of the GC-dots was calculated to be about 12.4% using quinine sulfate in 0.1 M H2SO4 as standard at 360 nm excitation wavelength, which is higher than the previous reported study as shown in Table 1 . The entire synthesis process of GC-dots and multifunctional applications were illustrated in Fig. 4 .

The aqueous solution of the GC-dots displayed green fluorescence under 365 nm UV light. A group of researchers demonstrated that when C-dots comprise of carbonyl and carboxyl groups on the surface, it will certainly result in a number of common transient species in transient absorption spectroscopy [

                           56

                        ]. From the recent discoveries, it was confirmed that green luminescence of the nano-dots originated from the disordered edge states [

                           57

                        ]. Depending on the edge state of carbon backbone which holds carboxyl and carbonyl functionalities, the production of several special conformations can be augmented by combination of carbonyl and carboxyl functional groups in the vicinity at the edge of the nanoparticles. These functional groups and the hybridization of carbon backbone was responsible for the common origin of green emission [

                           56

                        ].

The FTIR spectra of the GC-dots/PAA film, and PAA film were represented in Fig. 6a. As discussed previously the FTIR spectrum of GC-dots revealed several functional groups such as O − H, N − H bond, C − N, CO, CC and CN stretching vibrations. Definitely, the ample polar functionalities at the surface of the GC-dots made them hydrophilic which leads to the good dispersion of C-dots in PAA solution. Peaks at 1058, 1460, 1687, 2931 cm−1 corresponding to C-O-C stretching vibration, CH bending, CO stretching, and CH2 group stretching vibration, respectively [

                              58

                           ]. Additionally, the FTIR spectra of PAA and GC-dots/PAA composite film present a peak at about 1252 cm−1, which was due to vibration band of CO. The FTIR spectrum of PAA film showed a broad absorption band at 3362–3655 cm−1 corresponding to O − H and/or N − H group stretching. However, in case of GC-dots/PAA composite film the absorption band in this range (3310–3699 cm−1) was broadened. The energy transition probability is associated with the properties of the functional groups present. For a particular functional group, the intensity of IR absorption band is relative to Fermi resonance, conjugate groups, H-bonds, and solvent effect [

                              59

                           ]. Moreover, the GC-dots/PAA film showed the same absorption peak in comparison with the PAA film indicating the possibility of the Fermi resonance and conjugate group effect can be omitted. For the present case, water was used as solvent in the preparation of PAA, GC-dots and GC-dots/PAA composite film. So, solvent effect cannot influence the IR vibration. Therefore from the discussion above, we can say the peak broadening is related to the hydrogen bonding which indicates the good miscibility between PAA and GC-dots.

In the absorption spectrum of the GC-dots (Fig. 3a) discussed previously, peak located at 252 nm can be assigned to the π-π* transitions of the sp2 domains, which cannot generate fluorescence signal [

                              60

                           ]. But the another peak at 325 nm was due to the trapping of the excited state energy of surface states, which can produce strong fluorescence signal [

                              61

                           ]. Additionally, at λex = 380 nm, the emission spectra of the GC-dots/PAA films were measured. Results showed that the emission spectrum of GC-dots/PAA composite films displayed a peak at 470 nm, which was consistent with the emission spectrum of GC-dots (Fig.S9), when excited at 380 nm. However, the pure PAA film showed almost negligible FL response at 380 nm excitation wavelength. The synthesis method of the GC-dots/PAA composite by simple solution mixing of GC-dots into PAA and its potential applications in sunlight conversion film and photo bleaching effect was schematically shown in Fig. 6d. The composite film had excellent flexibility and foldability as shown in digital photographs (Fig. 7
                           ). The films were bent and rolled up a number of times without having any crack or damage and exhibited green emission on UV excitation, which suggests for the potential application in sunlight conversion film.

Study and investigation on the living cells is one of the most significant fields in the research world as this technique used to study cancer cells and many fatal diseases. In the cell imaging experiment, fluorescent probe was used to show live cells under microscope. Herein, we have used AD-MSCs as our model cell line. Now the question is why stem cells? Stem cells are very significant for the understanding of native improvement and tissue regeneration, giving rise to tissue progenitor cells and in turn discriminate into tissue-forming cells [

                           62

                        ,

                           63

                        ]. Owing to the specialty of stem cells, the bio-labeling process experiences a substantial challenge and presently no such method is available for efficient direct bio-marking of stem cells [

                           64

                        ]. At the time of application of stem cells or their progeny for regeneration of tissues and organs, there is a critical requirement to describe the relative contribution to the regenerated tissues and organs from delivered cells vs. host cell. Therefore, long-lasting and biocompatible marking of stem cells is necessary in the area of regenerative medicine to better understand their migration, fate, and contribution to the regenerating tissues [

                           65

                        ]. The excellent optical properties of the GC-dots associated with their cytocompatibility and durability are convincing and have encouraged us to explore their potential in labeling of stem cells.

Fig. 10a displayed the image of intravenous injection of GC-dots (0.8 mg/mL) suspended normal saline into the superficial vein of rabbit ear. The intravenous inoculation of the GC-dots solution showed bright fluorescence under two photon microscope. For evaluation signal intensity in vivo, the ADMSCs were cultured and treated with GC-dots (0.8 mg/mL) for 24 h at 37 οC. Afterward, GC-dots labeled ADMSCs (6 x 105cells/mL) were suspended in normal saline and injected subcutaneously in the outer side of the ear (Fig. 10b). The two-photon fluorescence microscopy has advantages over normal one-photon fluorescence microscopy in terms of a larger penetration depth amenable for imaging while minimizing photodamageand bleaching, a higher spatial resolution and a lower background signal due to the highly non-linear and localized adsorption process [

   66

]. As depicted in the Fig. 10b, the two photon imaging of the subcutaneously injected labeled stem cells into the rabbit ear skin revealed good signal intensity. The arrows showed that GC-dots labeled stem cells exhibited clear green fluorescence under laser excitation of 880 nm. Two photon microscopic image of GC-dots labeled stem cell in fluorescence mode was shown in Fig.S12. In vitro and in vivo experiments suggested that GC-dots can function as newfangled multifunctional phototheranostic agent for fluorescence imaging in biomedical field. Liu et al. also reported the detailed and long term monitoring of ADSCs in vivo using organic nanodots [

   67

].

To obtain information about the mechanism of GC-dots internalization, cells were pretreated with various inhibitors of different endocytotic mechanisms. The fluorescence microscopy images of the pretreated cells with various inhibitors and the untreated control cells (without inhibitors) after incubation with GC-dots were shown in Fig. 11 . Prior to the use of inhibitors, we conducted the cellular uptake experiment at low temperature 4 °C. As depicted in Fig. 11a-c, compare to the 37 °C condition, the fluorescence signal of the GC-dots incubated cells at 4 °C (Fig. 11d-f) under fluorescence microscope were found to be very weak. These result indicated that energy-dependent endocytosis was involved in the cellular uptake mechanism [
68
]. For the filipin III-treated cells the fluorescence intensity (Fig. 11g-i) was significantly decreased, suggesting that caveolae-mediated endocytosis may be the major pathway in the uptake process of GC-dots. For chlorpromazine-treated cells, the fluorescence level (Fig. 11j-l) was hardly changed, indicating that clathrin-mediated endocytosis was not involved for GC-dots entry. These results indicated that both energy-dependent and energy-independent pathways are involved in the GC-dots entry into the cells, and caveolae-mediated endocytosis may be the primary pathway. Therefore, the uptake of nano-meter sized GC-dots were attributed to the good bio-compatibility of C-dots and penetration into the cells by means of endocytosis. Kang et al. reported that the small-size SWCNTs (50–100 nm) internalization via caveolae-mediated endocytosis [
69
]. The schematic diagram of intracellular fluorescence imaging was depicted in Fig. 12 .
